{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"fba88197-ab54-4e98-ba7f-759c67309296","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, look in these locations:\n\n1. **Apple Crash Reports** — macOS automatically generates `.ips` crash reports:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Files are named like `YourApp_YYYY-MM-DD-HHMMSS_machinename.ips`.\n\n2. **Console.app** — Open Console → sidebar → \"Crash Reports\" to browse them with a GUI.\n\n3. **Core dumps** — Disabled by default on macOS. To enable:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   sudo sysctl kern.corefile=/tmp/cores/core.%P\n   ```\n   Then reproduce the crash. The core file appears at the configured path.\n\n4. **`lldb`** — You can attach or load a core dump:\n   ```bash\n   lldb ./YourApp -c /path/to/core\n   ```\n\nThe `.ips` crash reports (JSON format) include the faulting thread, stack traces, and register state — usually enough to start diagnosing without a full core dump.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f228daf1-fda8-4e3a-8c96-8c9a8c60b83a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT app on macOS when `createdump` isn't available. This is a knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":342,"requestId":"608F:2A830E:2E18B0:3BB84E:69FFE3D6"},"id":"ccb9fcca-63df-4b1a-913b-8e19ef1b9b8d","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:48:15.931Z","parentId":"5f181e63-9d45-44ea-8f28-f3ea0ee03dd2"}
